Intro

As we discussed in the first session, R was developed for “statistical computing and graphics”, so it provides a bunch of functions for working with statistical and probability problems1.

Probability distributions

R provides functions to simulate many probability distributions (binomial, normal, uniform, beta, Poisson, etc.).

Every distribution that R handles has four functions. There is a root name, for example, the root name for the normal distribution is norm. This root is prefixed by one of the letters:

  • p for “probability”, the cumulative distribution function (c. d. f.)

  • q for “quantile”, the inverse c. d. f.

  • d for “density”, the density function (p. d. f.)

  • r for “random”, a random variable having the specified distribution

For the normal distribution, these functions are pnorm, qnorm, dnorm, and rnorm . Examples:

pnorm(q = 169, mean = 170, sd = 7.5, lower.tail = TRUE)
[1] 0.4469649
pnorm(q = 169, mean = 170, sd = 7.5, lower.tail = FALSE)
[1] 0.5530351
qnorm(p = .4469649, mean = 170, sd = 7.5, lower.tail = TRUE)
[1] 169
rnorm(n = 10, mean = 170, sd = 7.5)
 [1] 174.7272 156.1960 171.5395 165.2153 185.7647 164.0907 166.0450 170.8663
 [9] 178.4002 175.4177

Binomial distribution:

Suppose there are 12 multiple choice questions in an Maths class quiz. Each question has 5 possible answers, and only 1 of them is correct.

n_experiments <- 12
n_success <- 4
prob_success <- 1 / 5

Find the probability of having EXACTLY four correct answers if a student attempts to answer every question at random:

dbinom(x = n_success, size = n_experiments, prob = prob_success)
[1] 0.1328756

Find the probability of having four or less correct answers:

pbinom(q = n_success, size = n_experiments, prob = prob_success)
[1] 0.9274445

Random numbers from the binomial distribution:

rbinom(n = 10, size = n_experiments, prob = prob_success)
 [1] 3 1 2 4 3 3 0 4 3 4

Simulation of the first experiment:

mean(rbinom(n = 1000, size = n_experiments, prob = prob_success) == n_success)
[1] 0.141

Plotting results:

df_binomial <- data.frame(
  success = 0:n_experiments,
  prob = dbinom(
    x = 0:n_experiments,
    size = n_experiments,
    prob = prob_success
  )
) %>%
  mutate(highlight = ifelse(success == n_success, as.character(n_success), "other"))

df_binomial %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(
    x = factor(success),
    y = prob,
    fill = highlight
  )) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_text(
    aes(label = round(prob, 3), y = prob + 0.01),
    position = position_dodge(0.9),
    size = 3,
    vjust = 0
  ) +
  labs(
    title = paste("Probability of X =", n_success, "successes."),
    subtitle = "binomial(12, .2)",
    x = "Successes (x)",
    y = "Probability"
  ) +
  theme_light()

Poisson distribution:

The Poisson distribution is the probability distribution of independent event occurrences in an interval (mainly time) when we know the average (\(\lambda\)) of occurrences per interval.

If there are twelve cars crossing a bridge per minute on average, the probability of having seventeen cars crossing the bridge in a particular minute is:

dpois(x = 17, lambda = 12)
[1] 0.03832471

The probability of having sixteen or less cars crossing the bridge in a minute is in the lower tail of the probability density function. This is:

ppois(q = 16, lambda = 12, lower.tail = TRUE)
[1] 0.898709

Simulating experiments

We can use R to simulate the outcome of experiments when we know the distribution of probabilities.

With choose() we can simulate combinations easily according to the binomial coefficient: \(\binom{n}{k} = \frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}\)

# How many football lineups can we choose with a squad of 25 players (for the sake of simplicity, consider any player can be goalkeeper)
choose(n = 25, k = 11)
[1] 4457400
factorial(25) / (factorial(11) * factorial(25-11))
[1] 4457400

If we want to know which are the specific combinations, we can use the function combn()

With replicate(), we can repeat experiments to get probabilities. Imagine we want to know, in average, how many times must a 6-sided die be rolled until a number n turns up. With sample() we simulate rolls:

sample(x = 1:6, size = 1)
[1] 4

And using while statement we can execute sample until the desired condition is met:

# Roll dice until we get n
desired_number <- 6
x <- 0
while(x != desired_number) {
  x <- sample(x = 1:6, size = 1)
  print(x)
}
[1] 1
[1] 1
[1] 3
[1] 2
[1] 4
[1] 3
[1] 1
[1] 1
[1] 2
[1] 4
[1] 3
[1] 4
[1] 4
[1] 5
[1] 6

So now, we can pack the code inside a function:

roll_dice <- function(desired_number) {
  # This function simulates the number of dice rolls to get a desired number
  i <- 0      ## A counter of rolls
  x <- 0
  while(x != desired_number) {
    x <- sample(x = 1:6, size = 1)
    i <- i + 1
  }
  return(i)
}

# The result of this function is the number of rolls to get a 6
roll_dice(desired_number = 6)
[1] 3
# So, in average, after n experiments, we need y rolls to get desired number
mean(replicate(n = 1000, expr = roll_dice(desired_number = 6)))
[1] 6.191

Correlation

Correlation is a measure of linear relationship between two variables.

loan_data <- fread(
  file = "./DATA/loan_data.csv",
  header = TRUE,
  sep = ",",
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE,
  dec = "."
)
cor(loan_data$annual_inc, loan_data$loan_amnt)
[1] 0.4035427
loan_data %>%
  select(annual_inc, loan_amnt, int_rate, installment) %>%
  cor(use = 'complete.obs') %>%
  corrplot(
    title = 'Correlation coefficients',
    addCoef.col = TRUE,
    tl.col = 'black',
    number.digits = 3
  )

loan_data$grade_num <- as.numeric(as.factor(loan_data$grade))

cor(loan_data[, c('grade_num', 'default')], use = "complete.obs")
          grade_num   default
grade_num 1.0000000 0.1523802
default   0.1523802 1.0000000

A different form of “correlation” used for binary variables: the AUC. Given a numerical variable X and a binary variable Y, AUC represents the probability of an instance Y = 1 having a higher value on X than and instance Y = 0. That is, if we order Y by X, the probability of placing a 1 before than a 0 It goes from 0.5 to 1, where 0.5 is that of a random order.

Simulated data:

n <- 30000
mean_default      <- 2
mean_not_default  <- 2
set.seed(42)

# Change the value of the mean of rnorm() in data frame default to explore different values of AUC

default <- data.frame(result = "default",
                      score = rnorm(n = n, 
                                    mean = mean_default, 
                                    sd = 1)
                      )

not_default <- data.frame(result = "not default",
                          score = rnorm(n = n, 
                                        mean = mean_not_default, 
                                        sd = 1)
                          )

data <- rbind(default, not_default)

ggplot(data, aes(result, score)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(data, aes(score, fill = result)) +
  geom_histogram(position = "identity",
                 alpha = 0.2,
                 bins = 100) +
  theme_minimal()

AUC: It measures the probability that the scoring of a randomly chosen default is higher than that of a randomly chosen not_default.

The standard deviation / sqrt(N), where N is the number of observations, gives us an estimation of the error:

errors <- c()

for (i in obs) {
  error <- sd(loan_data[1:i, default], na.rm = T) / sqrt(i)
  errors <- append(errors, error)
}

errors
[1] 0.133333333 0.042857143 0.031446604 0.013309632 0.009406619 0.006588908
[7] 0.004043570 0.002863393 0.002294650

  type = 'b',

  ylab = 'Standard error'

With the estimated value of the mean and its standard error, we can build a range of possible values for the “population” value named Confidence Interval The confidence interval represents the range of values for the mean that we could observe, with certain probability, in case we make another estimation of the mean with a new sample.

How likely would we observe values on that range? It depends upon the ” confidence level”. If we define a 95% Interval, then 95% of the times we estimate the mean with another sample we would observe values on the interval. That is why it is commonly said that, for example, “we are 95% sure that the mean will be between the 95-IC range”.

Values of the 90, 95 and 99 confidence level:

qnorm(p = c(0.05, 0.95))
[1] -1.644854  1.644854
qnorm(p = c(0.025, 0.975))
[1] -1.959964  1.959964
qnorm(p = c(0.005, 0.995))
[1] -2.575829  2.575829
pnormGC(
  round(qnorm(p = c(0.025, 0.975)), digits = 2),
  region = "between",
  mean = 0,
  sd = 1,
  graph = TRUE
)

[1] 0.9500042

95-Interval of Confidence for the mean with 1000 observations:

n <- 1000

obs <- sample(size = n, x = loan_data$default, replace = F)

prop <- mean(obs)

error <- sd(obs) / sqrt(length(obs))

conf_int <-
  c(
    Inferior = prop - qnorm(p = 0.975) * error,
    Superior = prop + qnorm(p = 0.975) * error
  )

conf_int
  Inferior   Superior 
0.07864751 0.11535249

Little demonstration:

df_conf_int <- data.frame()

for (i in 1:100) {
  n <- 1000
  obs <- sample(size = n,
                x = loan_data$default,
                replace = F)
  prop <- mean(obs)
  error <- sd(obs) / sqrt(length(obs))
  conf_int_temp <-
    c(
      Inferior = prop - qnorm(p = 0.975) * error,
      Superior = prop + qnorm(p = 0.975) * error
    )
  df_temp <- data.frame(inf = conf_int_temp[1],
                        sup = conf_int_temp[2])
  df_conf_int <- rbind(df_conf_int, df_temp)
}

df_conf_int <- df_conf_int %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = 'experiment')

ggplot(df_conf_int) +
  geom_segment(aes(
    x = experiment,
    xend = experiment,
    y = inf,
    yend = sup
  ), color = "grey") +
  geom_point(
    aes(x = experiment, y = inf),
    color = 'green',
    size = 2,
    alpha = 0.5
  ) +
  geom_point(
    aes(x = experiment, y = sup),
    color = 'green',
    size = 2,
    alpha = 0.5
  ) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = mean(loan_data$default), col = 'red') +
  geom_text(aes(
    x = 'Inferior1',
    y = mean(loan_data$default) - 0.001,
    label = round(mean(loan_data$default), 3)
  ),
  col = 'red',
  size = 3) +
  coord_flip() +
  xlab('Experiment') +
  ylab('Estimated confidence interval') +
  theme_light() +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank()
  )

Hypothesis testing

t-test

Let’s see if there’s genuine differences in the default rate amongst grade D and G:

\(H_{0}\) \(->\) There is no difference between both groups, the observed difference in the mean is due to chance.

\(H_{1}\) \(->\) There is a statistically significant difference between both groups.

gD <- loan_data$default[loan_data$grade == 'D']

gG <- loan_data$default[loan_data$grade == 'G']

mean_diff <- mean(gD) - mean(gG)
mean_diff
[1] -0.07843335
t_test <- t.test(gD, gG, alternative = 'two.sided')
t_test

Exercise

  1. On average, how many times must a 6-sided die be rolled until you get a desired_number n times in a row?
roll_dice_n <- function(n) {
  i <- 0
  x <- 0
  while(x != 6) {
    x <- mean(sample(x = 1:6, size = n, replace = TRUE))
    i <- i + 1
  }
  return(i)
}

roll_dice_n(6)
[1] 10020
mean(replicate(n = 1000, roll_dice_n(3)))
[1] 212.621
